---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import TreeWorld from '../components/TreeWorld.astro';
---

<Base
  active="how"
  title="How storytree works"
  description="A live map of your system, a library where intent is decided, and a harness that holds the agents to it — built for people shipping software with AI agents."
>
  <!-- intro -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
      <h1>The model isn't the bottleneck anymore.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        If you build with AI&nbsp;agents, you've felt the shift: writing the code stopped being the
        hard part. The hard part is <em>seeing</em> what got built, <em>trusting</em> it, and keeping
        several humans and a swarm of agents pointed at the same thing. storytree is three pieces
        aimed squarely at that — a live <strong>map</strong> of your system, a shared
        <strong>library</strong> where intent gets decided, and a <strong>harness</strong> that
        holds the agents to it.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="grid grid--3 trio">
        <div class="card trio__card">
          <span class="trio__tag">The map</span>
          <p>A top-down, glanceable picture of the whole system, coloured by health. You read it instead of re-reading diffs and chat logs — and so do the agents.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card trio__card">
          <span class="trio__tag">The library</span>
          <p>Where humans and agents agree what's being built and what "done" means — <em>before</em> a line is generated, so review checks the work against intent.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card trio__card">
          <span class="trio__tag">The harness</span>
          <p>A deterministic, human-in-the-loop lane that holds the model to the same gates a team would — nothing counts as done until a check that was failing is made to pass.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE MAP + demo -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">The map · observability</p>
      <h2>A satellite view of your system, not a scroll-back of the chat.</h2>
      <p>
        An agent writes 400 lines in a minute. Now the work isn't writing — it's working out what
        changed and whether it's healthy. In Sonar's mid-2026 survey of 1,100+ developers, 96% said
        they don't fully trust that AI-generated code is functionally correct — yet only about half
        always verify it before it ships. The tools that watch agents mostly watch the <em>run</em> —
        traces, tokens, cost. Almost
        none of them show you the <em>system</em>: what now exists, and what's actually been checked.
      </p>
      <p>
        storytree does. Every project is a living map you read at a glance. Each tree is a
        <strong>story</strong> — one slice of the product. Its colour is its health, the garden around
        it is its capabilities, and the roads between trees are what depends on what. Glance to see
        what exists and what's holding; drill into a node and read the code when you actually need to.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="wrap">
      <TreeWorld />
    </div>

    <div class="wrap prose legend-note">
      <p class="muted">
        Above is a made-up system — a fictional team-chat backend called <strong>Cohoot</strong> —
        shown in storytree's real map view. Hover or tap any tree to inspect a story; click to pin it
        and light up everything it depends on. (Invented data, not storytree's own roadmap.)
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p>
        And the map isn't only for you — it's what the <strong>agents</strong> read too. The instinct
        is to dump the whole repo into context and let the model sort it out, but quality drops long
        before the window is full — attention is a <em>finite resource with diminishing marginal
        returns</em> as it fills (Anthropic's framing). Hand an agent a compact, top-down graph of the system with
        health states and it spends its budget on the task instead of burning it re-deriving the maze
        — and rotting its own context on the way in.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- the grain -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">The grain</p>
      <h2>Big things are made of small, checkable things.</h2>
      <p>
        Zoom into a story and it's made of smaller pieces, each one small enough to pin down on its
        own. The idea is old, boring, and it works: you don't get to call something done because it
        feels done — you get to call it done when there's evidence.
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid--3 ladder">
        <div class="card">
          <span class="dot dot--healthy"></span><strong>Story</strong>
          <p class="muted">A whole, useful slice — the kind of thing a newcomer can point at. Checked by walking it end to end, the way a real person would actually use it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="dot dot--healthy"></span><strong>Capability</strong>
          <p class="muted">An organ inside a story. Checked by testing its parts wired together, for real — no faking the hard bits with a mock.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="dot dot--healthy"></span><strong>Contract</strong>
          <p class="muted">A single behaviour, pinned by one focused automated test. The smallest brick — and the one thing an agent can't talk its way past.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- DAG as health monitor -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">The graph · triage</p>
      <h2>A file tree tells you where things are. A health graph tells you where they're broken.</h2>
      <p>
        storytree assumes the whole system can be drawn as a graph — stories to capabilities to
        contracts, with dependency edges between them. That one assumption turns the map into a
        real-time health monitor. Health flows along the edges like blast-radius analysis: when a
        contract fails, everything that leans on it is marked suspect, and the red branch tells you —
        and the next agent — exactly where to look.
      </p>
      <p>
        You can see it in the map above. One failing branch — the real-time fan-out that everything
        live depends on — drags presence and typing down with it. A flat file tree would just show you
        where those files live. The graph shows you that they're all downstream of the same broken
        thing. <strong>The red branch is the work; everything else can wait.</strong>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- the harness / gates -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap band2">
      <div class="band2__inner prose">
        <p class="eyebrow">The harness · proof</p>
        <h2>"All tests pass" is a claim, not a proof.</h2>
        <p>
          Agents don't just hallucinate — they reward-hack. Made to chase green checks, they'll
          hardcode an output, quietly trim the test suite, or game the harness instead of fixing the
          thing. This isn't a thought experiment: in late-2025 safety work, a reward-hacking model was
          caught faking a passing run with a bare <code>sys.exit(0)</code>; a 2026 benchmark across
          frontier models logged exploit rates as high as ~14%. A green check can mean "the work is
          done" — or "the harness got played."
        </p>
        <p>
          So storytree doesn't take the agent's word for it. A node only goes green when a check that
          was <em>failing</em> is made to pass for the right reason — and a person signs off. Health is
          a machine-checkable contract measured against evidence, not a status the model reports about
          itself, and the generated code is hard-linked to the node it claims to satisfy. Every part of
          the map is signal for one question: <em>did the agents build what I actually asked?</em>
        </p>
        <ul class="checks">
          <li>An idea or a concern can come from anyone — you don't have to write code to raise one.</li>
          <li>It's argued in the open, where the reasoning stays on the record instead of in a scrolled-away thread.</li>
          <li>If it becomes work, that work has to pass its gate before it counts — a failing check made to pass, not a vibe.</li>
          <li>A human still says the final yes. A green light is a request for review, not an automatic merge.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="band2__caveat">
          Honest scope: green means <em>the checks passed</em> — not that the code is flawless. The map
          compresses the cost of seeing what's been built and checked; it doesn't replace reading the
          code or your CI. It's a sharper place to point your attention, not a guarantee.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- the library / coordination -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">The library · coordination</p>
      <h2>Decisions that don't scroll away in Slack.</h2>
      <p>
        The models can already code, and they keep improving. The hard part is coordinating the
        <em>intent</em> of several humans — and when an agent emits hundreds of lines in seconds, the
        humans are the bottleneck. Anthropic's own 2026 read on agentic coding
        names the gap: AI&nbsp;agents now touch a majority of dev work, but only a small slice of tasks
        is fully hand-off-able — supervision and judgement are what's scarce. Review turns into
        archaeology: reverse-engineering intent from a finished diff.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>library</strong> is where that intent lives. Humans and AI&nbsp;agents discuss the
        system, record the decision and the agreed definition of done <em>before</em> generation — so
        at review time you're checking the diff against what everyone agreed, not reconstructing it
        from scratch. Because it's all one shared map, the work can be massively parallel without
        becoming chaos: you can see who's touching what, where the proof stands, and what's still just
        an idea. We lean into that on purpose — at its best, steering a project here is closer to
        playing a cosy city-builder than parsing terminal output.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- why this is different -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">Why this is different</p>
      <h2>Most tools give an agent one surface. storytree draws the whole map.</h2>
      <p>
        An agent has to hold three things at once, and it's bad at all three: <strong>what's true</strong>
        (the decisions, the definitions), <strong>what the system is</strong> (the code), and
        <strong>what needs doing</strong> (the work). The honest fix isn't a bigger context window — it's
        to stop making the agent hold them in its head and put each on a wall it can read.
      </p>
      <p>
        We're not the first to any one of these, and that's reassuring. Steve Yegge's
        <strong>Beads</strong> is a dependency-aware issue graph that replaces the markdown TODO files
        that rot between sessions — a work surface, done well. Anthropic's <strong>Skills</strong> and
        Letta's memory blocks are curated knowledge surfaces — a library. And the code map is old:
        <strong>Aider</strong> has shipped a tree-sitter "repo map" since 2023, and tools like CodeGraph
        let an agent query a code graph instead of grepping. Smart people arrived at each surface on
        their own — which usually means an idea is right, not clever.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two things we haven't seen anyone else do. <strong>One:</strong> put all three together —
        knowledge, code, and work as one deliberate model, not one pillar in isolation.
        <strong>Two, and it's the one we care about:</strong> draw the map at the altitude of
        <em>intent</em>. The repo-map tools read the code that already exists and compress it — a
        faithful mirror of <em>what's there</em>. A mirror can't tell you what a system is <em>for</em>,
        who owns what, or whether a thing is done. storytree's map is the other way around: the code has
        to satisfy <em>it</em>. A <strong>story</strong> is the size of a service — "the message store",
        "the billing ledger"; a <strong>capability</strong> is an organ inside it; the line between them
        is how you prove it, and the dependency edges fall out of the proofs instead of being hand-drawn.
        Spec-driven tools get close to authoring intent, but tend to flatten it into a per-feature
        checklist that's thrown away when the feature ships. A standing, two-tier map of intent that
        outlives any one task still looks like open ground.
      </p>
      <p class="muted">
        We might be wrong that the unification is worth it — maybe one surface is enough and the other
        two are overhead. We'd bet the other way. The field is already walking toward all three from
        three different directions; we just think you arrive faster if you draw the whole map at once.
      </p>
      <p class="see-survey">
        <a href="/landscape/">See the full survey — who's built what, the field's convergence, and the
        honest case that this is mostly renaming →</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- cta -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap prose cta-card">
      <h2>That's the how.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        The <em>why</em> — why build it out in the open at all, what we commit to, and how to take
        part — is its own thing. If the approach resonates, that's the door to come through.
      </p>
      <div class="hero__cta">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/get-involved/">Why this exists · get involved →</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/constitution/">Read the constitution</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .trio { margin-top: 1.6rem; }
  .trio__card { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; }
  .trio__tag {
    align-self: flex-start;
    font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--evergreen-deep);
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sage-leaf); padding-bottom: 0.15rem;
  }
  .trio__card p { margin: 0; color: var(--ink-soft); font-size: 0.96rem; }

  .legend-note { margin-top: 1rem; }
  .legend-note p { font-size: 0.92rem; margin: 0; }
  .see-survey { margin-top: 1.4rem; font-size: 1.0rem; }
  .see-survey a { font-weight: 600; }
  .ladder { margin-top: 1.3rem; }
  .ladder .card p { margin: 0.4rem 0 0; }
  .ladder .card strong { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.12rem; }
  .ladder code, .band2 code, .prose code {
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.86em; background: var(--surface-2); padding: 0.05em 0.35em; border-radius: 5px;
  }

  .band2 {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-left: 5px solid var(--evergreen);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow);
  }
  .band2__inner { padding: clamp(1.6rem, 4vw, 2.8rem); max-width: 46rem; }
  .band2__caveat {
    margin-top: 1.3rem; padding-top: 1.1rem; border-top: 1px dashed var(--line-strong);
    font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-soft);
  }
  .checks { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 1.2rem 0 0; display: grid; gap: 0.7rem; }
  .checks li { position: relative; padding-left: 1.9rem; color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .checks li::before {
    content: ""; position: absolute; left: 0; top: 0.35em;
    width: 1.15rem; height: 1.15rem; border-radius: 999px;
    background: var(--evergreen-soft);
    box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 2px var(--evergreen);
  }
  .checks li::after {
    content: ""; position: absolute; left: 0.34rem; top: 0.62em;
    width: 0.42rem; height: 0.24rem; border-left: 2px solid var(--evergreen); border-bottom: 2px solid var(--evergreen);
    transform: rotate(-45deg);
  }
  .cta-card { text-align: center; max-width: 40rem; }
  .cta-card .hero__cta { justify-content: center; }
  em { font-style: italic; }
</style>
